"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867030","Home Office","false","2018-03-23","<p>The information you have requested is not included in statistics published by the Home Office.</p><p>Information on the total number of Tier 2 refusals can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017/list-of-tables#visas</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-23T13:53:09.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867030/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867030/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-19","Psychiatry: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Tier 2 visa applications sponsored by the NHS for NHS child and adolescent psychiatrists were turned down in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","133148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867031","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>We are piloting in-cell telephony and basic computers in two prisons – HMP Wayland and HMP Berwyn. The purpose is for prisoners to manage some of their own day-to-day tasks that would normally be managed by officers on paper, freeing up officers to focus their time on the important task of reforming offenders.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot is still running in both prisons. We are monitoring and evaluating the benefits to assess the impact on prisoner safety and rehabilitation, and on officers’ ability to do their jobs more effectively.</p><p> </p><p>Work has also been undertaken in preparation for piloting digital capabilities in a number of other sites, detail of which are below.</p><p> </p><ul><li>HMP Durham, HMP Wandsworth, HMP Holme House, HMP High Down, HMP Kirklevington Grange, YOI Cookham Wood, HMP Eastwood Park, HMP Moorland, HMP Chelmsford, HMP Exeter, HMP Liverpool, HMP Leeds, HMP Bristol, HMP Swaleside, HMP Aylesbury, HMP Manchester and HMP Guys Marsh.</li></ul><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","133150","2018-03-22T17:45:51.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867031/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867031/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-19","Prisons: Computers and Telephones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2018 to Question 132158, on Prisons: Computers and Telephones, whether there were any prisons in which the pilot was started but ended before its scheduled completion.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","133149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867032","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>We are piloting in-cell telephony and basic computers in two prisons – HMP Wayland and HMP Berwyn. The purpose is for prisoners to manage some of their own day-to-day tasks that would normally be managed by officers on paper, freeing up officers to focus their time on the important task of reforming offenders.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot is still running in both prisons. We are monitoring and evaluating the benefits to assess the impact on prisoner safety and rehabilitation, and on officers’ ability to do their jobs more effectively.</p><p> </p><p>Work has also been undertaken in preparation for piloting digital capabilities in a number of other sites, detail of which are below.</p><p> </p><ul><li>HMP Durham, HMP Wandsworth, HMP Holme House, HMP High Down, HMP Kirklevington Grange, YOI Cookham Wood, HMP Eastwood Park, HMP Moorland, HMP Chelmsford, HMP Exeter, HMP Liverpool, HMP Leeds, HMP Bristol, HMP Swaleside, HMP Aylesbury, HMP Manchester and HMP Guys Marsh.</li></ul><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","133149","2018-03-22T17:45:51.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867032/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867032/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-19","Prisons: Computers and Telephones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2018 to Question 132158, on Prisons: Computers and Telephones, whether there were any prisons in which work was undertaken in preparation for the pilot but the full pilot was not commenced.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","133150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867033","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-22","<p>​The UK closely followed preparations for the first round of elections held in Sierra Leone on 7 March 2018 and called for all parties to deliver free, fair, inclusive and peaceful elections. We fully supported the EU Election Observation Mission, which deployed 28 long term observers and a further 40 short term observers. We share the conclusions drawn by international and domestic observation missions that the result reflects a robust and credible process.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-03-22T16:09:54.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867033/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867033/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-19","Sierra Leone: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the extent to which the first round of elections held in Sierra Leone on 7 March 2018 were conducted in a free, fair and transparent manner.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","133151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867034","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-22","<p>The Government of Sierra Leone has placed a temporary ban on female genital mutilation/cutting (FGM/C) during the March 2018 elections. This was in place for the first round of voting and remains in place during the run off vote for the Presidency. The ban was put in place to prevent candidates paying for girls to undergo the practice as a method of influencing voters. The UK is in full support of this ban. In our messages to all presidential candidates we asked for the protection of the rights of women and girls. The UK Government has consistently lobbied the Government of Sierra Leone to fulfil their international obligation to legislate against the practice of FGM/C and to approve a National Strategy to support this. We will raise this issue as a priority with the new government and we stand ready to support implementation of the Strategy once approved. We will also work to build coalitions of support to end the practice and lobby government to take the necessary action.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-03-22T15:18:15.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867034/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867034/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-19","Sierra Leone: Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent discussions she has had with her counterpart in Sierra Leone on the temporary ban on female genital mutilation introduced by that Government; and if she will make representations to that Government to make the ban permanent.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","133152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867035","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could be obtained only at disproportionate cost. To provide this information, a manual search of the record of every female prisoner held at New Hall during 2017 would be required.</p><p> </p><p>We currently do not record the number of women who give birth in prisons centrally but consideration will be given on recording this information locally on prison systems.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-22T17:57:26.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867035/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867035/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-19","New Hall Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women in HMP New Hall gave birth while imprisoned in 2017.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","133153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867036","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>Data relating to Mother and Baby Unit (MBU) applications is published annually and the latest published data available is for 2016/17 (at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017</a>). In 2016/17, 15 applications for a place on an MBU were approved by the MBU Admission Board at New Hall and 13 women were received into the unit there during that time. This would include women who were pregnant and women who had a child under 18 months. National data for 2017/18 will be published in the HMPPS Annual Digest on 26 July 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Not all women whose applications are approved at New Hall will immediately take up a place on the unit. Some may take a place nearer, or after, giving birth, some may subsequently decide not to take up their place and some may move to an MBU at another establishment.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-22T17:53:05.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867036/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867036/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-19","New Hall Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many pregnant women at HMP New Hall were given a place in a mother and baby unit in 2017.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","133154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867037","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-22","<p>During 2016/17 (the year for which the most recent published data is available), 3 women returned to the general prison population at New Hall following a separation from their baby or babies.</p><p> </p><p>Women in Mother and Baby Units (MBUs) may be separated from their children for a number of reasons. The most common would be the child reaching an age where it would be in its best interests to live outside of the prison environment, but there will also be cases where the mother decides that she wishes to hand out the child to family or friends or where the mother’s prison behaviour mean that separation would be in the best interests of the child.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-22T14:06:38.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867037/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867037/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-19","New Hall Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women in HMP New Hall who had babies or infants resident with them in prison had those children taken away from them in 2017.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","133155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867038","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>NHS Digital have provided us with data that detail a count of finished consultant episodes, with a primary diagnosis of diabetes or peripheral arterial disease and a main procedure of lower limb amputation. These are tabulated by strategic health authority area for the financial years between 2008-09 and 2011-12 and clinical commissioning group for treatment for the financial years between 2012-13 and 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>The Clinical Coding team have advised that I73.9 - Peripheral vascular disease unspecified includes but is not limited to peripheral arterial disease.</p><p> </p><p>Tables and data are attached.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-22T17:12:42.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867038/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867038/answer","PQ133156 Tables.docx","PQ133156 Tables.docx","PQ133156 attached document","PQ133156 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867038/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Orthopaedics : Cardiovascular System and Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many lower limb amputations associated with peripheral arterial disease and diabetes have taken place in the NHS in each year since 2008-09; and how many of those amputations have taken place in each (a) strategic health authority area prior to 2012-13 and (b) clinical commissioning group area since 2012-13 .","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","133156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867039","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the estimated total cost of limb amputations. The table shows the cost of amputation of single or multiple limb but does not differentiate between lower or upper and single or multiple amputation stump or partial foot amputation procedures for diabetes or arterial disease.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Estimated total cost (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Limb amputations unspecified</p></td><td><p>Amputation for diabetes or arterial disease</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£53.0</p></td><td><p>£23.0</p></td><td><p>£76.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£52.7</p></td><td><p>£45.0</p></td><td><p>£97.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£56.5</p></td><td><p>£44.4</p></td><td><p>£100.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£59.1</p></td><td><p>£47.1</p></td><td><p>£106.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£59.2</p></td><td><p>£48.3</p></td><td><p>£107.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Department of Health and Social Care, Reference Costs</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the estimated total cost of rehabilitation for the amputation of limb in each of the last five years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Estimated costs (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£5.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£7.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£6.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£7.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£6.8</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Department of Health and Social Care, Reference Costs</p><p> </p><p>The data source for the table is from reference costs, which are the average unit costs to National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts of providing defined services in a given financial year to NHS patients. Reference costs for acute care are collected by healthcare resource group, which are standard groupings of clinically similar treatments which use common levels of healthcare resource. Reference costs represent the cost to the NHS provider, not the cost to the commissioner.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","133158","2018-03-22T11:46:46.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867039/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867039/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Orthopaedics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much the NHS has spent on lower limb amputations in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","133157"
