"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867081","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-26","<p>Throughout this process, Ministers and senior officials from the Department for Exiting the European Union have spoken with delegates from groups representing UK nationals in the EU, including representatives of British in Europe, to hear their views and concerns. Our Embassies and Ambassadors in the EU 27 have also engaged extensively with the UK communities in their host states.</p><p><strong><br></strong>All UK nationals legally resident in the EU before the end of the implementation period, 31 December 2020, will fall under the Citizens’ Rights part of Withdrawal Agreement. This is an agreement that gives people more certainty about residence, healthcare, pensions and other benefits. As negotiations progress we will continue to work in the interests of our nationals to reach a final deal that is in the mutual interests of citizens living across the continent.</p>","Fareham","Suella Fernandes",,"2018-03-26T16:33:17.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867081/answer","Biography information for Suella Braverman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867081/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-19","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans he has to meet representatives of British in Europe to discuss the effect of the UK leaving the EU on UK citizens living in non-UK, EU countries.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","133199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867082","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-27","<p>We welcome the statements from President Mnangagwa on his intention to implement a wide range of economic and political reforms, including his commitment to holding free and fair elections this year. Implementation of these reforms will be critical for Zimbabwe to realise its desire for international re-engagement.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-03-27T12:14:51.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867082/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867082/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-19","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political situation in Zimbabwe.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","133200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867083","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-27","<p>Preston Park and Worthing A27 Roadside monitoring sites were chosen to measure background and roadside pollution concentrations respectively within reporting zone 10 (Brighton, Worthing and Littlehampton) and is sited in accordance with EU requirements for compliance purposes. In 2016, the data captured at the Worthing A27 Roadside site did not meet the requirements for assessment under the Air Quality Directive. The site was only brought into operation in October 2016 so the required data capture of at least 75% for the year could not be achieved. For 2017 we expect both sites to be included in the assessment subject to data validation procedures.</p><p> </p><p>The national model is designed to meet the specific requirements for assessing compliance with the nitrogen dioxide limits, as set out in the Ambient Air Quality Directive. The High Court found [in Mr Justice Garnham’s judgment, handed down on 21 February 2018] that our national air quality modelling and monitoring are compliant with these legal requirements. Data that does not meet the Directive requirements cannot be incorporated in this assessment, but should continue to be used by local authorities to monitor air quality as part of the Local Air Quality Management process.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-27T08:18:39.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867083/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867083/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-19","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of his Department’s national air quality monitoring data from Preston Park and Worthing for the purpose of assessing the compliance of Brighton and Hove Local Authority area with EU limits of nitrogen dioxide NO2 air pollution; if he will make it his policy to include Brighton and Hove City Council local NO2 pollution monitoring data from (a) North Street Low Bus Emission Zone and (b) Lewes Road link to the universities in the national assessment; if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of the national model assessment in determining which cities comply with the NO2 limit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","133201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867084","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Brent North to the answer I gave him on 21 March, UIN: 133081 &amp; 133082.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-03-22T17:02:52.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867084/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867084/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-19","Import Duties: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his European Union counterparts on the potential merits of bringing a case to the World Trade Organisation on the US Administration's proposed steel and aluminium tariffs.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867085","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-22","<p>Whilst we remain a Member State the EU is responsible for initiating and defending trade disputes on the UK’s behalf.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-03-22T17:05:04.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867085/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867085/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-19","Import Duties: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he has received legal advice on effectiveness of bringing a case to the World Trade Organisation on the introduction of steel and aluminium tariffs by the US administration.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867086","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-22","<p>The Government believes it is right that WTO members can, via application of the Article XXI exemption, apply certain protections for the protection of security interests. Moreover, it is right that channels exist under WTO rules to challenge the application of Article XXI exemptions. The Government assesses each case on its merits.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-03-22T17:07:10.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867086/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867086/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-19","Trade Barriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the effect on World Trade Organisation rules of using national security as a reason to impose trade barriers.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867087","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-22","<p>I refer the Hon. Member for Brent North to the answer I gave him on 21 March, UIN: 133084.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-03-22T17:11:17.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867087/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867087/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-19","Iron and Steel: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to increase market access for UK steel to (a) existing and (b) new markets as a result of the tariffs on steel proposed by the US administration.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867088","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-23","<p>The use of payroll companies is an internal matter for private sector suppliers. Such information is not held by Government.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-23T11:47:35.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867088/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867088/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-03-19","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information he holds on the use of payroll companies by strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","133206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867089","Department for Education","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Association of Colleges (AoC) does not have any duties in relation to early years recruitment.</p><p> </p><p>The article stated that the colleges with incorrect information have already corrected their websites. The department has written to the AoC to ask them to remind their members of the change in English and maths requirements for entry to level 3 early years job roles made in April 2017.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-27T16:04:32.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867089/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867089/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-19","Pre-school Education: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the article in Nursery World, Colleges cause confusion by stating need for GCSEs, published on 19 March 2018, if he will publish the correspondence between his Department and the Association of Colleges of their duties in relation to early years recruitment.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","133207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867090","Department for Education","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency funding guidance for young people does not include information on which qualifications are valid for careers in particular sectors. Therefore we do not intend to update the guidance to include information on functional skills as an entry route for work in early years settings. Functional skills have always been eligible for funding in programmes for students who are also studying early years qualifications. However, students on a 16 to 19 study programme must meet the condition of funding for maths and English, which may require some students to study GCSE rather than functional skills.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-03-27T15:59:28.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867090/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867090/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-19","Pre-school Education: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that the Education and Skills Funding Agency’s publication, Guidance for Young People 2017 to 2018 reflects the policy of his Department to reinstate functional skills as an entry route for those wanting to work in early years settings.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","133208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867091","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>MBRRACE-UK is currently undergoing detailed analysis of the recent neonatal death statistics; this includes mortality adjusted in relation to important risk factors e.g. premature birth, congenital anomaly. NHS England will await the results of MBRRACE-UK’s analysis prior to making any new strategic plans relating specifically to the 0.1% increase in neonatal deaths in 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department remains committed to our ambition to halve the rates of neonatal and maternal deaths, stillbirths and brain injuries that occur during or soon after birth by 2025. Further information about the measures in place to achieve the ambition can be found here in the National Maternity Safety Strategy:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662969/Safer_maternity_care_-_progress_and_next_steps.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662969/Safer_maternity_care_-_progress_and_next_steps.pdf</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-27T12:04:51.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867091/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867091/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Infant Mortality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to tackle the increase in infant mortality identified by the Office for National Statistics from 2.6 neonatal deaths per 1,000 births in 2015 to 2.7 neonatal deaths per 1,000 births in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","133209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867092","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>We welcome the findings of this report, which acknowledges the genuine progress that England has made in many areas in recent years. We are committed to giving children the best start in life, and we will look closely at the report’s recommendations.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-27T16:24:51.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867092/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867092/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his Department's policies of the recommendations of the Nuffield Trust report International comparisons of health and wellbeing in early childhood, published in March 2018.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","133210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867093","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>Early years providers may be eligible for existing business rates reliefs, including Small Business Rate Relief and Charitable Rate Relief. They will benefit from reductions to business rates of over £10 billion.</p><p> </p><p>The Government keeps all taxes, including reliefs, under review.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-26T13:33:26.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867093/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867093/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-19","Pre-school Education: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has plans to extend business rates relief to early years providers before the next re-evaluation of rates in 2021.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","133211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867094","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-27","<p>EU sectoral sanctions, which have been in place since 2014, target parts of the Russian energy sector. Coal is not currently included under these sanctions. In response to the Salisbury incident, we continue to consider the full range of potential levers, both domestically and through international fora.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-03-27T12:59:44.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867094/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867094/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-19","Russia: Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, if the Government will include imports of coal from Russia in the list of sanctions against that country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","133212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867095","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-22","<p>Two employees of the Carillion group of companies with director in their titles are still involved with the Private Finance Initiative (PFI) Company to deliver the PFI scheme for the Royal Liverpool and Broadgreen University Hospital NHS Trust. Neither employee has been a Director on the Board of Carillion PLC.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-22T15:51:39.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867095/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867095/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many former Carillion directors are employed as advisers on the completion of the Royal Liverpool University Hospital.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","133213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867096","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>All seven of Great Britain’s active coal plants generated at some point in the week commencing 26 February. These are; West Burton, Eggborough, Aberthaw B, Fiddlers Ferry, Ratcliffe, Drax and Cottam. This is in line with the normal functioning of the electricity market.</p><p>We have announced measures to ensure that all unabated coal generation will close by 2025. In the meantime, coal can be an important bridge to new, lower-carbon technologies, including gas, and can provide important and economic capacity in the interim period until coal units close.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:26:01.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867096/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867096/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-19","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which UK coal-fired power stations supplied the National Grid during the week commencing 26 February 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","133214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867097","Home Office","false","2018-03-23","<p>Hydrochloric acid is a reportable substance under Part 4 of Schedule 1A to the Poisons Act 1972 (as amended by the Deregulation Act 2015). This means that retailers are required to report any suspicious transactions, significant losses and thefts to the national contact point.</p><p>The Home Office uses a range of methods to measure the effectiveness of these controls, including monitoring numbers of suspicious activity reports, and the number that lead to further investigation. Comparing this information with the information available before the controls were in place indicates that the controls have made it easier for authorities to detect attempts to purchase high risk chemicals for illicit purposes.</p><p>The substances controlled by the Poisons Act 1972 and the means of evaluating efficacy are continuously reviewed and updated to manage the current threat.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-23T12:02:28.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867097/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867097/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-19","Acids: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the regulation of the sale of concentrated hydrochloric acid online.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","133215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867098","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Healthy Start Scheme helps to encourage a nutritious healthy diet for more than 326,000 pregnant women, families and children under four from low income households. The Government recommitted to the Healthy Start scheme in the 2016 plan ‘Childhood Obesity: A plan for Action’.</p><p> </p><p>The scheme has also been developed in other ways. For example, the addition of frozen fruit and vegetables in 2011 allows families to get more with their vouchers.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-03-27T12:05:50.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867098/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867098/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Health Start Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department plans to make of the effect of the Healthy Start scheme on the nutrition of pregnant women and young children; and if he will increase the value of the vouchers to meet the increasing cost of food.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","133216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867099","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>In order to determine continued eligibility for Healthy Start vouchers and vitamins, it is necessary for beneficiaries to contact the Healthy Start Issuing Unit (HSIU) to confirm their eligibility status. This is to ensure that beneficiaries are receiving the correct amount of vouchers per the number of children in the household.</p><p> </p><p>Calls to the HSIU cost no more than calls to standard United Kingdom landline phone numbers. An e-mail contact form is also available.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","133218","2018-03-27T12:07:15.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867099/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867099/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Healthy Start Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will remove the necessity for mothers to contact the Healthy Start Unit to inform them of the birth of their baby in order to receive Healthy Start vouchers and vitamins.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","133217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867100","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>In order to determine continued eligibility for Healthy Start vouchers and vitamins, it is necessary for beneficiaries to contact the Healthy Start Issuing Unit (HSIU) to confirm their eligibility status. This is to ensure that beneficiaries are receiving the correct amount of vouchers per the number of children in the household.</p><p> </p><p>Calls to the HSIU cost no more than calls to standard United Kingdom landline phone numbers. An e-mail contact form is also available.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","133217","2018-03-27T12:07:15.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867100/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867100/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-19","Healthy Start Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will introduce a free telephone number for Healthy Start recipients to contact the Healthy Start Issuing Unit.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","133218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867101","Department for Education","false","2018-03-22","<p>These figures are published in our Further education and skills geography data tool: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-further-education-and-skills" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fe-data-library-further-education-and-skills</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The number of apprenticeship starts in the East Midlands in the last five years, split by level are in the public domain and are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Apprenticeship level</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Intermediate (Level 2)</p></td><td><p>28,500</p></td><td><p>26,770</p></td><td><p>29,880</p></td><td><p>28,510</p></td><td><p>26,160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Advanced (Level 3)</p></td><td><p>19,610</p></td><td><p>12,730</p></td><td><p>16,370</p></td><td><p>17,280</p></td><td><p>18,270</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Higher (Level 4+)</p></td><td><p>890</p></td><td><p>790</p></td><td><p>1,810</p></td><td><p>2,280</p></td><td><p>3,110</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All apprenticeship starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>49,010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>40,290</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>48,060</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>48,080</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>47,540</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Figures rounded to the nearest 10</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-03-22T17:53:38.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867101/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867101/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-19","Apprentices: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many apprenticeships starts there were in the East Midlands; and what the level was of each of those starts in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","133219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867102","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>There are now over 60 suppliers operating in the domestic energy market, some of which offer very competitive prices, especially for fixed term tariffs. We have already halved the time it takes to switch supplier to 21 days (including the statutory cooling off period). Ofgem is leading a programme across industry to introduce faster and more reliable switching by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>Smart metering will make it easier and more convenient for consumers to engage with their energy use so they can reduce their bills and identify the best tariff and energy supplier for their needs. Smart Energy GB, who are responsible for national consumer engagement on smart meters, have found that 86% of people with a smart meter said they made energy saving changes to their behaviour.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:05:06.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867102/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867102/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-19","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that consumers can access the cheapest energy tariffs without the need to install a smart meter.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","133220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867103","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-27","<p>The contractor for the Credit Union Expansion Project (CUEP) facilitated access to a standardised banking service. This banking platform allows credit union members to receive a range of banking services and benefit from more affordable credit. The platform is currently used by three credit unions with a total of approximately 16.5k members and allows these members to benefit from 24 hour online access to their accounts, and receive faster payments on a loan on the same day, usually within 4 hours.</p><p> </p><p>CUEP led to a number of credit unions to merge, and others to work together to develop standardised products and deliver local marketing campaigns to increase membership. CUEP also contributed to credit unions on the platform to increase the amount and value of loans made.</p><p>CUEP ended on 16 February 2018 and it is too early to say what effect it had on the credit union sector. It should be noted that the credit union sector has grown over the lifetime of CUEP. As of January 2018, credit unions in Great Britain serve over 1.1 million adult members and have total assets of £1.5 billion and £815m in loans.</p><p>The project will undertake an evaluation as part of the project closure.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","133223","2018-03-27T12:48:52.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867103/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867103/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-19","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the outcome of the Credit Union Expansion Project.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","133221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867104","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-27","<p>DWP engaged a contractor to deliver the Credit Union Expansion Project (CUEP). It is the responsibility of the contractor to include any disclosure relating to the project within their accounts.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-03-27T12:56:03.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867104/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867104/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-19","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to publish the accounts of the Credit Union Expansion Project.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","133222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867105","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-27","<p>The contractor for the Credit Union Expansion Project (CUEP) facilitated access to a standardised banking service. This banking platform allows credit union members to receive a range of banking services and benefit from more affordable credit. The platform is currently used by three credit unions with a total of approximately 16.5k members and allows these members to benefit from 24 hour online access to their accounts, and receive faster payments on a loan on the same day, usually within 4 hours.</p><p> </p><p>CUEP led to a number of credit unions to merge, and others to work together to develop standardised products and deliver local marketing campaigns to increase membership. CUEP also contributed to credit unions on the platform to increase the amount and value of loans made.</p><p>CUEP ended on 16 February 2018 and it is too early to say what effect it had on the credit union sector. It should be noted that the credit union sector has grown over the lifetime of CUEP. As of January 2018, credit unions in Great Britain serve over 1.1 million adult members and have total assets of £1.5 billion and £815m in loans.</p><p>The project will undertake an evaluation as part of the project closure.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","133221","2018-03-27T12:48:52.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867105/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867105/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-19","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the Credit Union Expansion Project had on access to finance for people who are financially excluded.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","133223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867106","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-27","<p>We are unable to provide data from 2010 as records only go back to 2014 with the formation of the Animal &amp; Plant Health Agency.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Manchester Airport</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date/Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Plant Health Inspectors</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Heathrow Airport</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date/Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Plant Health Inspectors</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>There are currently no vacancies in the Plant Health and Seeds team based at Manchester airport. There are currently 5 vacancies in the equivalent team based at Heathrow. A recruitment process to fill the vacancies is currently being undertaken.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","133225","2018-03-27T11:11:16.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867106/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867106/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-19","Animal and Plant Health Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many Plant Health Inspectors have been stationed at (a) Heathrow and (b) Manchester airports in each year since 2010."