"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867136","Department for Education","false","2018-03-22","<p>The government is committed to free speech within the law – this does not include hate speech, incitement to violence or terrorism. Free speech is protected in universities by law (under the Education (no 2) Act 1986) and plays a crucial role in generating rigorous debate, advancing understanding and allowing students to challenge conventional wisdom and discuss controversial subjects.</p><p> </p><p>We would expect universities to take appropriate action against violent incidents or against threats to speaker events, involving law enforcement if necessary. We would be very concerned if a university restricted an individual’s freedom of speech within the law due to concerns about reaction.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-03-22T17:57:25.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867136/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867136/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-19","King's College London: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Government has made an assessment of the implications for its policy of restrictions imposed by King's College London on the freedom of speech of Israeli speakers on its campus following disruption by violent students.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","133254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867137","Department for Education","false","2018-03-23","<p>We plan that the construction skills fund will open for bids next month.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-03-23T13:08:53.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867137/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867137/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-19","Construction: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, on what date his Department plans to publish the application criteria for the construction skills fund announced in the Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","133255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867138","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-22","<p>At Autumn Budget, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced that we will raise the Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap by a total of up to £1 billion in areas of high affordability pressure, for local authorities that are ready to start building new homes. Local authorities will be able to bid for increases in their caps from 2019/20, up to a total of £1 billion by the end of 2021/22. We will set out more details shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-22T11:36:49.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867138/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867138/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-19","Housing Revenue Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to publish the (a) details of what constitutes high affordability and (b) criteria used in determining how support will be allocated under the Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap announced in Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","133256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867139","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-22","<p>The 26-30 railcard trial is led by the rail industry and we await the results of the trial with interest.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-22T16:35:32.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867139/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867139/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-19","Railways: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department was made aware of the decision to expand the 26-30 railcard trial to 10,000 extra participants.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","133257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867140","Home Office","false","2018-03-22","<p>A person who is of the first generation born outside the United Kingdom to a British citizen would usually be a British citizen by descent, including where they were born before 1 January 1983, with a few exceptions.</p><p>The 1981 Act also contains provision for children born outside the UK to British citizens by descent, who have retained a close connection to the UK to register as British citizens.</p><p>Since the British Nationality Act 1981 was introduced amendments have been made to allow children of unmarried British fathers and children of British mothers, who would have become British citizens had women been able to pass on their citizenship in the same way as men, to register as British citizens.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-22T10:50:31.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867140/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867140/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-19","British Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if the Government will introduce retrospective changes to the law, to allow people who were born outside the UK  before 1 January 1983 to a British parent, to inherit their parent's UK citizenship.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","133258"
