"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865116","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>Rule 35 of the Detention Centre Rules 2001 sets out the process by which doctors in immigration removal centres must report to the Home Office cases in which they have concerns that:</p><ul><li>a detainee’s health is likely to be injuriously affected by detention (35(1));</li><li>a detainee is suspected of having suicidal intentions (35(2)); or</li><li>a detainee may have been the victim of torture (35(3)).</li></ul><p>On receipt of a Rule 35 report, the Home Office caseworker must review the appropriateness of the detainee’s continued detention in conjunction with consideration of the adults at risk in immigration detention policy.</p><p>The total number of releases from all Immigration Removal Centres (IRC) because of Rule 35 during Q3 2017 is 102 and is published as part of the Transparency publication under the category ‘Reports made by a medical practitioner under Rule 35 by place of detention’. This can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a></p><p>Management information indicates that of the 102 total releases in Q3 2017, 26 of these were from Yarl’s Wood IRC. This information has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics and as internal management information is subject to change.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-21T13:00:30.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865116/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865116/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-16","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer 13 March 2018 to Question 131298 on Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre; of the 98 reports made by a medical practitioner under Rule 35 in Yarl's Wood during Q3 of 2017, how many caseworker reviews of the appropriateness of continued detention led to a detainee's release from detention.","false","Biography information for Yvette Cooper","Normanton, Pontefract and Castleford","Yvette Cooper","132983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865117","Home Office","false","2018-03-21","<p>The Dublin III Regulation is a long-standing mechanism between EU Member States to determine responsibility for examining asylum claims.</p><p>The Home Office published comprehensive data on the number of transfers into the UK from other Dublin states as part of the most recent quarterly Immigration Statistics release on 22/02/2018. The relevant statistics can be found at as_22_q, asylum volume 5 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2017-data-tables</a></p><p>The published statistics are broken down by each article of the Regulation and it is Article 8 which outlines the criteria for the Member State responsible for examining the asylum claims for unaccompanied minors.</p><p>It is important to note that the full data set includes children transferred as dependent family members under other articles of the Regulation, however a breakdown of these families by age is not published.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-21T13:04:52.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865117/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865117/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-16","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 13 March 2018 to Question 131300, how many of the 148 arrivals into the UK from Greece under the Dublin Regulation in Q4 of 2017 were children.","false","Biography information for Yvette Cooper","Normanton, Pontefract and Castleford","Yvette Cooper","132984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865118","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-21","<p>By 31<sup>st</sup> March 2020, TransPennine Express expect to have 44 new trains available, with 29 of their older trains refurbished ‘as new’.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-21T16:29:11.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865118/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865118/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-16","Trains: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 March 2018 to Question 130371, how many (a) new and (b) refurbished TransPennine Express trains will be released by the year 2020.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","132985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865119","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-22","<p>DFID has many programmes which address the needs of Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs), all of which are subject to regular review of their effectiveness. At a global level, the UK is supportive of the idea of a UN High Level Panel on IDPs to assess the effectiveness of the current response to internal displacement and galvanise further political and operational action. We are discussing this closely with other interested States and UN agencies.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-22T15:21:22.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865119/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865119/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-16","Developing Countries: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of its support for internally displaced people; and whether her Department plans to take any steps to improve the effectiveness of that support.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","132986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865120","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-21","<p>Defra’s public consultation, launched on 12 March, on the proposal to introduce a ban on the use of electronic training collars includes anti-bark collars.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-21T11:40:53.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865120/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865120/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-16","Electronic Training Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the consultation on Animal welfare: banning the use of electronic training collars for cats and dogs, published by his Department in March 2018, whether anti-bark dog collars are covered within the scope of that consultation.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","132987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865121","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-29","<p>The consultation closes on 27 April. It is normal practice to respond within three months.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-29T16:27:59.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865121/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865121/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-16","Electronic Training Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the consultation on Animal welfare: banning the use of electronic training collars for cats and dogs, published by his Department in March 2018, what the timescale is for his Department to publish a response to that consultation.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","132988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865122","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-29","<p>In our consultation on a proposal to ban the use of electronic collars we have proposed to make it an offence to use an e-collar, or even to put one on a cat or dog, or be in charge of a cat or dog that is wearing one. We also want to hear views about what these proposals will mean for the sale of e-collars and whether any further restrictions will be required beyond what the government is proposing in order to deliver our objective to end their use.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-29T16:13:45.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865122/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865122/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-16","Electronic Training Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing a ban on the sale of electric shock collars.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","132989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865123","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-26","<p>In 2014/15, 2015/16 and 2016/17 DWP headcount was 89805, 84698 and 83851 respectively. In addition to annual salaries our staff were paid an annual, non-consolidated, performance-related bonus. For the majority of our most junior grades, AA to EO, the amounts were, on average in each year £463.</p><p> </p><p>Total payments were:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>in-year non-consolidated award</p></td><td><p>end of year non-consolidated award</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>£3,991,001</p></td><td><p>£38,141,345</p></td><td><p>£42,132,346</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/2016</p></td><td><p>£4,095,000</p></td><td><p>£35,979,154</p></td><td><p>£40,074,154</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/2017</p></td><td><p>£5,341,766</p></td><td><p>£36,017,851</p></td><td><p>£41,359,617</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-26T16:42:52.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865123/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/865123/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-16","Department for Work and Pensions: Incentives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions how much was awarded to staff of her Department in bonuses in each of the last three financial years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","132990"
